article.description:
A career night for Kelly Schumacher and the
rest of the Indiana Fever had the appreciative crowd singing their
praises.
article.headline: Schumacher has 22 points vs. Silver Stars
article.linkText: Schumacher's career night leads Fever to record win
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- A career night for Kelly Schumacher and the
rest of the Indiana Fever had the appreciative crowd singing their
praises.

Schumacher scored a career-high 22 points and tied a career high
with nine rebounds as the Fever beat the San Antonio Silver Stars
81-47 Wednesday night.

When she fouled out with 3 minutes left, the crowd serenaded her
performance with a prolonged "Shoooo!"

"We needed to get our mojo back and I think we got it back,"
said Fever coach Nell Fortner.

Did they ever.

It was the largest margin of victory in Indiana's four-year
history, and the Fever's late 38-point lead was their largest ever.
They held San Antonio to 24 percent shooting, a team record for
lowest percentage allowed.

Schumacher continues to flourish in a reserve role, showing why
the Fever (11-9) made her their first-round pick in 2001. Fortner
said it was easily Schumacher's best all-around game.

"I think what she finally realized was, `Hey, when I get my
minutes, I've got to get in there and get after it," Fortner
said. "You never know how long you're going to get to stay."

Schumacher, whose previous high was 15 points a year ago, sank
her first five field goals and finished 7-for-9 from the floor. Her
two 3-pointers matched her season total. The second gave the Fever
a 75-43 lead.

Schumacher, a 6-foot-4 center, was 2-for-5 this season from
3-point range and usually caught grief from her teammates when she
fired one up. Not this time.

"I'm kind of a little uneasy about it, but it shows I'm not
because I'm still taking them," she said.

Schumacher entered this season with a 3.7 career scoring average
in limited playing time but has blossomed this year. She leads the
Fever in blocks and is 16-for-21 from the floor in the last four
games.

"I got a little bit more of an opportunity to play a few more
minutes and I was confident shooting my 3-point shot," Schumacher
said.

The Fever avoided losing three straight for the first time this
season. They also improved to 9-1 at home.

Natalie Williams scored 12 points, and Tamika Catchings and
Nikki McCray each had 10 for the Fever, who shot 52 percent from
the floor.

Marie Ferdinand led San Antonio (6-15) with nine points.

"It seems we hang on to the negative things that happen during
the game instead of letting them go and overcoming," San Antonio's
Adrienne Goodson said.

Indiana broke the game open with a 23-8 run in the second half,
capped by a 3-pointer by Coretta Brown. That put the Fever ahead
65-38 with 8:05 left.

"That second half was a real exhibition of some really positive
things for this team," Fortner said.

The Stars held an early three-point lead and were tied at 20
with 7:50 left in the first half. The Fever, however, ended the
half on a 16-7 run.

"We just took to it to them," Williams said. "We just tried
to push the ball because we knew they'd get tired."

Catchings made a 3 from the top of the arc and Williams, playing
her first game against her former team, added consecutive baskets
as the Fever led 36-27 at the half.

Williams said the familiarity helped her.

"I knew what every single player was going to do and how they
did their moves," she said.

The Stars never got closer than nine points again.
